latestPosts.caption:
Episode 3 of Fashion Tip Tuesdays 👛

Stay hands free using these simple dupatta hacks to keep you moving freely through the party!

1. With the help of pins, attach a choker to both ends of your dupatta leaving about an inch at the tip, tighten the choker with the help of its tieback, creating a beautiful cape look.

2. To frame the blouse with a V shape, pin both ends of the dupatta together and tuck this at the centre front of your lehenga, secure it at the shoulder, leaving you with a double border look.

3. For a more fitted finish, drop both ends of the dupatta evenly at front and secure the mid section with a pin at the back, the upper layer of the dupatta will hide this pin, creating a fancy over coat look.

4. Put your accessories to use by slightly running one end of the duppata through a ring and secure this with a pin, wear the ring on whichever hand suits you best and throw the other end over your shoulder.

5. For the final tip, place the right end of the duppata over your left shoulder and drop its entire left side to the front, secure both at the shoulder with a pin and with the help of a kamarbandh / belt create a stunning cinched waist look over your dupatta.

Which style did you like the most? 

#stylingideas #dupattastyle #dupattahacks #fashiontiptuesdays

latestPosts.caption:
Episode 7 of fashion tip Tuesdays! 🤌🏻

Let’s try these simple hacks to elevate this season’s fav triangular scarfs🤍 

1. Starting off easy with a classic off shoulder knot but knot the front in a bow rather than the regular knot, for that additional pop.
2. For those bad hair days, knot the thinner ends of the scarf as per your desired length, interchange the sides of the scarf ends (left over right) and throw this around your neck, the bigger section of the scarf creates a hood.
3. Next lay the wider end of the triangular scarf over your neck and throw the thinner ends over opposite shoulders (back to front), using these thin ends create a bow over the triangular bit, you now have a chic bow tie bandana.
4. Put your rings to use with this hack, untie the bow from the last hack, retaining the bandana look, then run a ring through the thin ends to the highest length possible and secure the tips of the scarf in a knot at the back. You can leave this as it is over your bust, or take the band created by the ring and slide it over your hair to create a stunning hairband.
5. Lastly, throw the right end of the scarf over your left shoulder and run a ring through that end ( leaving just a few inches) wrap the left end around the bust (left to right). Now from the back take the left tip of the scarf and run it through the ring, and just like that you’ve created an adjustable crop top to go over your plain sweater and tees.

Would you try these styles?

#fashiontiptuesdays #fashiontips #stylehacks #scarfstyle

latestPosts.caption:
Let’s get ready for Christmas! When you can’t find the perfect Christmas party outfit, DIY one! I’ve used my satin saree to make this beautiful evening gown and absolutely loved it 🤌🏻 Also kept my makeup minimal and glowy using @reachedmars products! 
My go-to products for this radiant, dewy makeup look are:
	• Mars Hydra Glow Primer: The perfect base for that smooth, lit-from-within glow.
	•Mars Zero Blend weightless Foundation: Lightweight and hydrating, giving my skin that flawless, natural finish.
	•Mars Cover Rangers all in one palette as my contour: Subtle yet defining—adding just the right amount of depth.
 •Mars Blush Hour Sunkissed liquid blush: A pop of color for that fresh, flushed
 •Mars Lipstick (shade- Best Shot): The final touch, tying it all together with a soft, effortless charm 🤌🏻

How to make this DIY gown: Take a satin or flowy saree and tie two corners from the same side, draping them over one shoulder. Repeat the same on the other side and secure the saree at your waist with a ribbon. Move the entire length of the saree to the back, pleat the right end, and tuck it into the ribbon, leaving a front slit. Do the same with the left end. Tuck the back length neatly into the ribbon, then add a belt to hide the tucks. To finish, slide one sleeve off your shoulder for a chic asymmetrical evening gown look :)

Would you try this look?
